// SECTION 4 INSTRUMENTAL VARIABLES

// Exercise 1 {Artificial Data}


**********************************************
// Load data
webuse "ivreg2.dta",clear

// 1. Plot y against x
twoway (scatter y x) (lfit y x)

// 2. Estimate model
reg y x in 1/10		// 10 observations
est store t10
reg y x in 1/20		// 20 observations
est store t20
reg y x in 1/100	// 100 observations
est store t100
reg y x in 1/500	// 500 observations
est store t500
est table t10 t20 t100 t500
* All models have similar R-squared
* Coefficients change with sample size

// 3. Construct sample correlations of z1, z2 and x
corr z1 z2 x		// -cor- is an abbreviation for -correlate-
* corr(z1,z2)	=	-0.0153
* corr(z1,x)	=	 0.6208
* corr(z2,x)	=	 0.2895

// 4. Use z1 as instrument
qui ivreg y (x=z1) in 1/10
est store z110
qui ivreg y (x=z1) in 1/20
est store z120
qui ivreg y (x=z1) in 1/100
est store z1100
qui ivreg y (x=z1) in 1/500
est store z1500
est table z110 z120 z1100 z1500

// 5. Use z2 as instrument
qui ivreg y (x=z2) in 1/10
est store z210
qui ivreg y (x=z2) in 1/20
est store z220
qui ivreg y (x=z2) in 1/100
est store z2100
qui ivreg y (x=z2) in 1/500
est store z2500
est table z210 z220 z2100 z2500

// 6. Use z1 and z2 as instruments
qui ivreg y (x=z1 z2) in 1/10
est store z1z210
qui ivreg y (x=z1 z2) in 1/20
est store z1z220
qui ivreg y (x=z1 z2) in 1/100
est store z1z2100
qui ivreg y (x=z1 z2) in 1/500
est store z1z2500
est table z1z210 z1z220 z1z2100 z1z2500

// Exercise 2 {Return to Education for Married Women}


**********************************************
webuse "mroz.dta", clear

/* Before you start to answer the questions, notice that some of the variables
in the .dta file are given different names to what is stated in the exercises.
I have elected to rename all the relevant variables (also to lower case)
so that they match the exercise. But this is not necessary.
All the data remains the same.*/

// Rename variables
rename AGE age
rename CITY city
rename EDUC educ
rename EXPER exper
rename EXPERSQ expersq
rename FAMINC faminc
rename FATHEDUC fatheduc
rename HOURS hours
*rename HUSAGE husage
*rename HUSHRS hushrs
*rename HUSWAGE huswage
rename INLF lfp
rename KIDSGE6 kids618
rename KIDSLT6 kidsl6
rename LWAGE lwage
*rename MOTHEDUC motheduc
*rename MTR mtr
rename NWIFEINC nwifinc		// Note this variable is scaled differently from the definition in part 3. But we shall use the variable as given.
*rename REPWAGE repwage
*rename UNEM unem
rename WAGE wage

// 1. Estimate OLS model (restricting only to those in labour force)
reg lwage educ if lfp==1
est store ols
/* The coefficient for "educ" is significant and positive,
indicating that there is a positive correlation between education level and wages.
However the adjusted R-squared of the model is very low so this result is doubtful.*/

// 2. Estimate model with "fatheduc" as instrument for "educ"
ivregress 2sls lwage (educ=fatheduc) if lfp==1, small
est store iv
// Check validity of instrument
predict ivresid, resid
// Check covariances
corr educ fatheduc ivresid, cov
* A valid instrument, z, for variable x must satisfy the following conditions
* 	(a) cov(z,x)				/=	0
* 	(b) cov(z,u)				=	0
* In this scenario, we have
*	(a)	cov(fatheduc,educ)		=	3.345	/=	0
*	(b)	cov(fatheduc,ivresid)	=	0
* Conditions are met, and fatheduc is a valid instrument
// Compare with OLS estimates
hausman iv ols, constant sigmamore
* Do not reject H0, so OLS is efficient

// 3. Supply equation
// OLS
qui reg hours lwage educ age kidsl6 kids618 nwifinc
est store supplyols
// IV
ivregress 2sls hours (lwage = exper expersq) educ age kidsl6 kids618 nwifinc
est store supplyiv
predict u, resid
// Test endogeneity using Hausman's test
hausman supplyiv supplyols, constant sigmamore
* Reject H0, so there is evidence of endogeneity

// 4. First-stage regression
reg lwage educ age kidsl6 kids618 nwifinc exper expersq
test exper expersq
* exper and expersq are jointly significant.

// 5. Test validity of instruments
cor lwage exper expersq u, cov
/* The covariances between u and exper, and u and expersq are not zero.
Therefore the instruments are not valid. (See slide 20)*/

// Exercise 3 {Supply of Edible Chicken}


**********************************************
webuse "broiler.dta", clear

// Some of the variables are named differently in the dataset to how they are named in the task sheet
rename qproda qprod
rename pchick p
rename pbeef pb
rename meatex expts

tsset year, yearly

// Generate required variables
g lqprod	=	log(qprod)
g lp 		=	log(p)
g lpf 		=	log(pf)
g popgro 	=	100 * log(pop/L1.pop)
g lpb		=	log(pb)
g ly		=	log(y)
g lexpts	=	log(expts)

// 1. Estimate supply equation by OLS
reg lqprod lp lpf time L1.lqprod
est store ols

// 2. Estimate by IV
ivregress 2sls lqprod (lp = L1.lp lpb ly lexpts popgro) lpf time L1.lqprod, small
est store iv

// 3. Test for endogeneity using Hausman test
hausman iv ols, constant sigmamore
* Reject H0, so there is endogeneity

// 4. Check whether instruments are adequate
reg lp L1.lp lpb ly lexpts popgro
test L1.lp lpb ly lexpts popgro
* Reject null hypothesis therefore instruments are adequate.

// Exercise 4 {Cartel Data}


**********************************************
webuse "jec.dta", clear

// Generate required variables
g lq	=	log(quantity)
g lp	=	log(price)

// 1. Estimate by OLS
reg lq lp ice seas1 seas2 seas3 seas4 seas5 seas6 seas7 seas8 seas9 seas10 seas11 seas12
/* lq and lp are negatively correlated as expected. The higher the price,
	the less frequently rail transport is used*/
/* The icier the conditions, the more people will use rail transport*/
/* Season 1 and season 8 (January and August) appears to exhibit a reduction in rail users.
	This may be due to people being away for holidays
	(new year and summer in the norhter hemisphere?)*/
mfx compute, eyex at(mean)

// 2. Use "cartel" as instrument for "lp"
// First stage
reg lp cartel
* cartel is NOT weak because p < 0.05

// 3. Estimate by IV
ivregress 2sls lq (lp = cartel) ice seas1 seas2 seas3 seas4 seas5 seas6 seas7 seas8 seas9 seas10 seas11 seas12
mfx compute, eyex at(mean)
* Elasticity remains the same as OLS estimation.

est table IV1 IVmanual, se title("ivregress vs manual 2sls")
* The coefficient estimates are the same, but standard errors are different.
